==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Stroll
<hw>Stroll</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Strolled</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Strolling</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Cf. Dan.
<ets>stryge</ets> to stroll, Sw. <ets>stryka</ets> to stroke, to ramble,
dial. Sw. <ets>strykel</ets> one who strolls about, Icel.
<ets>strj<?/ka</ets> to stroke, D. <ets>struikelen</ets> to stumble, G.
<ets>straucheln</ets>. Cf. <er>Struggle</er>.]</ety> <def>To wander on
foot; to ramble idly or leisurely; to rove.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>These mothers <qex>stroll</qex> to beg sustenance for their
helpless infants.</q> <rj><qau>Swift.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To rove; roam; range; stray.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Stroll</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Stroll
<hw>Stroll</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A wandering on foot; an idle and
leisurely walk; a ramble.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Stroller</ent>⟦br⟧
